findings.description: Probable typo in PDF weight data for size 1800x900 reflected in graph. The 'Short' (550/600) weight is listed as 36 kg, which is significantly lower than the smaller 1800x600 unit (47 kg) and inconsistent with the 'Long' weight (77 kg). Expected weight is approx 62 kg.
findings.pdf_says: Page 9 Table, Row 1800x900: Vikt kg 550/600 = 36
findings.recommendation: Flag this value as a suspected PDF error in the graph metadata, similar to how GDMI FLEX headers were handled.

findings.description: Inconsistent dimension labeling in PDF. For size '600x300', the PDF lists Width (Bredd) as 300 and Height (Höjd) as 600. For all other rows in this family, the first number in the size label corresponds to Width. The graph faithfully reproduces this potential label/dimension swap.
findings.pdf_says: Page 16 Table, Row 1: Size '600x300', Bredd 300, Höjd 600
findings.recommendation: Verify if product is actually 300x600 (WxH) or if dimensions are swapped. Note discrepancy in graph.

findings.description: PDF internal inconsistency regarding housing lengths. Text on page 11 states lengths are 550/600 mm and 800/850 mm. The dimension table on page 12 lists them as 600/650 mm and 850/900 mm. The graph correctly prioritizes the table values.
findings.recommendation: Maintain current graph data (Table priority) but ensure the conflict note remains attached to the family node.

findings.description: PDF table headers for weight are identical (both labeled 1100/1150), making it impossible to distinguish short/long weights from headers alone. The graph has correctly inferred the first column is for the shorter 850/900 length based on value magnitude.
findings.pdf_says: Page 18 Table Headers: Col 1 'Vikt kg 1100/1150', Col 2 'Vikt kg 1100/1150'
findings.recommendation: No data change needed; graph interpretation is logically correct.

findings.description: Material availability inconsistency between PT and TT families. PDF Page 22 shows icons for both, but the 'RF' (Stainless) icon position appears blank/greyed out for PT, while TT in the graph includes RF. The text says 'Other materials on request'. Graph excludes RF for PT but includes it for TT.

gemini_pro.summary:
The Knowledge Graph is highly accurate and faithfully represents the provided PDF catalog, achieving a score of 98/100. The graph correctly captures all product families, dimensions, airflows, and material specifications. It has successfully navigated several significant errors within the PDF source text (such as the GDMI length contradiction and GDMI FLEX weight header duplication) by prioritizing tabular data and logical inference.

The reported findings are primarily documentation of defects in the PDF source itself (typos in weights, inconsistent dimension labeling) which the graph has reproduced or corrected. The only potential data improvement is clarifying the availability of RF (Stainless Steel) for the PT product family, which is ambiguous in the source document compared to its sibling product TT.

findings.description: Graph restricts GDMI materials to AZ and ZM only (and explicitly excludes RF/SF). PDF shows full material icon set for this family (FZ, AZ, RF, SF, ZM). This affects product recommendations in corrosive environments and stainless requests.
findings.pdf_says: GDMI page shows material icons: FZ, AZ, RF, SF, ZM (GDMI product page; icons at top).
findings.graph_says: Available materials: AZ, ZM (default); Material exclusions: ['RF','SF'].
findings.recommendation: Update GDMI material availability to include FZ, RF, SF in addition to AZ, ZM (unless there is a separate explicit PDF statement excluding them—none is shown on the GDMI page). Remove RF/SF exclusion.

findings.description: Graph allows AZ as an available material for GDMI FLEX. PDF shows only FZ, AZ, ZM icons? Actually the GDMI FLEX page shows icons FZ, AZ, ZM (top), but the text says it is made usually in ZM and 'Ej i rostfritt'. AZ is not contradicted; however the example code on GDMI FLEX page uses FZ (GDMI-FLEX-...-FZ). The graph sets ZM as default and includes FZ/AZ/ZM; this conflicts with the PDF example if your system expects default material from examples.
findings.pdf_says: GDMI FLEX product page: icons shown FZ, AZ, ZM; example code: GDMI-FLEX-600x600-850-R-PG-FZ.
findings.graph_says: Available materials: FZ, AZ, ZM (default ZM).
findings.recommendation: If 'default' must match the PDF ordering/example, set default material to FZ for GDMI FLEX (or store 'default_material_source=example_code'). Otherwise keep availability but clarify default rule.

findings.description: Graph states GDP is available in AZ/RF/SF/ZM besides FZ. PDF GDP page states 'GDP tillverkas vanligen i förzinkat' and shows full icon strip (FZ, AZ, RF, SF, ZM) at top, which implies availability is OK; but corrosion class statement is inconsistent across pages (see separate finding). No change needed for availability, but graph should cite icon evidence.
findings.pdf_says: GDP product page: material icons displayed FZ, AZ, RF, SF, ZM; text: 'tillverkas vanligen i förzinkat'.
findings.graph_says: Available materials: FZ (default), AZ, RF, SF, ZM.
findings.recommendation: Add source attribution: material availability derived from icon strip on GDP page (not just assumption).

findings.description: Graph hard-sets GDP corrosion class to C2. PDF 'Material' page defines FZ material as C3, while GDP product page states 'Korrosivitets klass C2'. This is a real dual-rating situation; graph keeps a note, which is good, but the material table in graph has no field for product execution vs raw material. This can cause downstream logic to incorrectly equate material class to product class.
findings.pdf_says: Material page: FZ Z275 = C3. GDP page: 'GDP tillverkas vanligen i förzinkat. Korrosivitets klass C2.'
findings.graph_says: GDP corrosion class C2; FZ material corrosion class C3.
findings.recommendation: Model two distinct properties: (a) product_execution_corrosion_class, (b) material_inherent_corrosion_class, and ensure rules use the right one.

findings.description: Graph sets construction to SINGLE_WALL_UNINSULATED and separately mentions door is double-wall insulated. PDF explicitly states cabinet is single-wall uninsulated but service door is double-mantlad and heat/condensation insulated. If graph has only one construction field, it is incomplete/ambiguous.
findings.pdf_says: GDB text: 'GDB levereras i oisolerat enkelväggsutförande med en servicelucka som är dubbelmantlad och värme/kondensisolerad som standard.'
findings.graph_says: Construction: SINGLE_WALL_UNINSULATED; Door insulation recorded (good) but overall construction may be interpreted as whole unit.
findings.recommendation: Keep cabinet construction and door construction as separate first-class fields (already partially done) and ensure any API consumer doesn’t treat 'Construction' as door construction.

findings.description: Graph code format includes a space: 'EXL-{width} {material}'. PDF example code uses hyphens and no space: 'EXL-600 AZ' appears in the example table, but rendered as 'EXL-600 AZ' (with a space) on the PDF; however typical product codes elsewhere are hyphen-separated (e.g., GDP-600x600-50-R-PG-FZ). This inconsistency will break code generation/parsing.
findings.pdf_says: EXL example: 'EXL-600 AZ' (as printed).
findings.recommendation: Standardize to one canonical delimiter scheme across the graph. If EXL truly uses space before material, store explicit regex/format and also a normalized_code variant (e.g., EXL-600-AZ) for system consistency.

findings.description: Graph code format includes a space: 'Filter profil-{width} {material}'. PDF example shows 'Filter profil-600 FZ' (space before material). Same risk as EXL for parsing and normalization.
findings.pdf_says: Filter profil example: 'Filter profil-600 FZ'.
findings.recommendation: As with EXL: store both the exact printed format and a normalized hyphenated format for reliable parsing.

findings.description: Graph says compatible filters are ['plan','pleat','panel'] with frame depths 25/50/100, but it does not explicitly constrain max filter depth to 100mm for GDP. PDF explicitly states 'Filter max djup 100mm' for GDP in the Sortiment overview, and GDP text describes 25/50/100mm standard depth. Missing max depth constraint can lead to wrong recommendations.
findings.pdf_says: Sortiment table: GDP 'Filter max djup 100mm'. GDP text: '...25, 50 eller 100 mm standarddjup...'.
findings.graph_says: Available frame depths [25,50,100]; no explicit max filter depth constraint field for GDP.
findings.recommendation: Add 'max_filter_depth_mm=100' for GDP and use it in compatibility logic.

findings.description: Graph stores max filter depths per length variant (450mm for short, 650mm for long) which matches PDF Sortiment table, but the family description mixes '550/600' with code '550' and '750/800' with code '750'. If your system interprets code as actual length in mm, it will be wrong for flanged versions (600/800).
findings.pdf_says: Sortiment table: GDB length 550/600 and 750/800; filter max 450mm and 650mm respectively.
findings.recommendation: Model two physical lengths per variant keyed by connection type (PG vs F40): e.g., length_mm_by_connection={PG:550, F40:600} and similarly {PG:750, F40:800}. Don’t collapse to a single integer code if it’s used as length.

findings.description: Graph uses length variants 600/650 and 850/900, which match PDF tables and Sortiment. However GDMI product text page states 550/600 and 800/850 (in the provided PDF images/text). If graph consumers trust narrative text, they may conflict. This needs explicit resolution in the graph.
findings.pdf_says: GDMI description text: '...två längder, 550/600 mm ... och 800/850 mm ...' but Sortiment and MÅTT table list 600/650 and 850/900.
findings.graph_says: Length variants: 600/650 and 850/900; notes a source conflict.
findings.recommendation: Keep table values as authoritative (good), but store all three: (a) table_length_set, (b) narrative_length_set, (c) resolved_length_set with resolution_reason='table_overrides_text'.

findings.description: Graph flags and stores a row labeled '600x300' but with Bredd=300 and Höjd=600 (swapped). In the PDF GDC FLEX table, the first row indeed shows '600x300' in the leftmost size column but the Bredd/Höjd columns show 300/600. This is a PDF internal inconsistency; graph must choose a canonical interpretation for WxH. If graph keeps 'Size=600x300', dimensional matching against duct sizes will fail.
findings.pdf_says: GDC FLEX MÅTT table row: Storlek shows '600x300' while columns show Bredd=300, Höjd=600.
findings.graph_says: Size key: 600x300; stored Bredd=300, Höjd=600; note says label may be reversed.
findings.recommendation: Canonicalize size keys to match the numeric Bredd/Höjd columns (i.e., store as 300x600), and keep the printed label in a 'pdf_label' field for traceability.

findings.description: Graph GDP table uses 'Size (WxH)' without carrying the PDF's combined size+length key (e.g., '200x200/250'). This is mostly fine because GDP length is fixed 250, but the PDF explicitly encodes it per row. Missing this can break exact cell-by-cell auditing and regeneration of PDF labels.
findings.pdf_says: GDP MÅTT table size column uses format like '200x200/250', '300x300/250', etc.
findings.graph_says: Size stored as 200x200 etc; length stored separately as 250.
findings.recommendation: Add 'pdf_size_label' for GDP rows or store composite key 'WxH/L' for exact round-tripping.

findings.description: Graph claims the PDF has an error for weight of GDB 1800x900 short length (550/600) as 36 kg. In the provided PDF table, that cell is indeed '36' under the 550/600 weight column. From an audit standpoint, graph must match PDF exactly, even if you believe the PDF is wrong. Marking it as a suspected error is fine, but the stored value must still be '36' if the graph intends to mirror the catalog (it currently does). The discrepancy is that the finding is not a data mismatch but a governance issue: you need a mechanism for 'catalog_error_override' vs 'catalog_value'.
findings.pdf_says: GDB MÅTT row 1800x900: Vikt kg 550/600 = 36 (as printed).
findings.recommendation: No numeric change. Add explicit fields: catalog_weight_kg and corrected_weight_kg (optional), plus approval workflow, so systems can choose whether to follow catalog or corrected engineering value.

findings.description: Graph lists PT available materials: FZ default, plus AZ/SF/ZM on request. PDF PT table shows only FZ in the material column and states 'Övriga material... tillverkas på begäran' (other materials on request) without specifying which. Adding SF/ZM/AZ may be acceptable, but it is not explicitly supported by the PDF and could be misleading.
findings.pdf_says: PT section: material table rows show 'FZ' and note: 'Övriga material, storlekar eller längder tillverkas på begäran.'
findings.graph_says: Available materials: FZ (default), AZ (on request), SF (on request), ZM (on request).
findings.recommendation: Change PT material availability to: default=[FZ], on_request=[UNSPECIFIED] or on_request=[AZ,RF,SF,ZM] only if you can cite a corporate rule. Best: store 'on_request=true' without enumerating unsupported materials.

findings.description: Graph enumerates TT on-request materials (AZ/RF/SF/ZM). PDF TT tables show only FZ and the same note 'Övriga material... på begäran' without enumerating. Same issue as PT.
findings.pdf_says: TT section: tables list material FZ; note: other materials on request.
findings.graph_says: Available materials: FZ default, AZ/RF/SF/ZM on request.
findings.recommendation: As for PT: do not enumerate specific on-request materials unless PDF explicitly lists them. Use a generic on_request flag or add source.

findings.description: PDF 'INNEHÅLL' lists 'PTT' (plan transition?) whereas the graph contains 'PT' but not 'PTT'. The PDF transition section shows PT and TT; 'PTT' appears only in the contents page. This is either a missing family in the graph or a PDF contents typo. From a completeness audit, it must be flagged.
findings.pdf_says: Contents page shows: 'PTT' and 'TT' under Övergång & Tillbehör.
findings.recommendation: Confirm whether 'PTT' is a separate product (e.g., PT with different connection) or a contents-page typo. If separate, add ProductFamily PTT and its size table; if typo, add an alias node mapping PTT -> PT with 'pdf_typo' note.

findings.description: Graph models option 'Förmonterad filterskena för polisfilter' but does not encode that it is tied to the 900/950 length variant and also that long variant can be used either for 450mm cylinder + polisfilter OR 600mm cylinder without polisfilter. This is partially captured as 'modes', but the option itself has code None and is not machine-actionable.
findings.pdf_says: GDC text: 'Längd 900/950 för 450 mm cylinder + polisfilter' and 'Längd 900/950 för 600 mm cylinder'.
findings.graph_says: Option exists with code None; modes string present.
findings.recommendation: Create explicit option entities: (a) polisfilter_rail=true applicable only when cartridge_length=450 and housing_length_variant=900/950; (b) cartridge_length_max=600 implies polisfilter_rail=false. Make it rule-driven rather than free-text.

findings.description: Same polisfilter option modeling issue as GDC: option has no code and is not structurally constrained by length vs cartridge length.
findings.pdf_says: GDC FLEX text includes the same three length statements (750/800 for 450, 900/950 for 450+polisfilter, 900/950 for 600).
findings.graph_says: Option exists with code None; modes string present.
findings.recommendation: Same as GDC: model polisfilter rail as a conditional configuration with explicit constraints.

findings.description: Graph includes polisfilter rail option (code None) but does not encode the PDF rule: 1100/1150 is for 600mm cylinder + polisfilter; 850/900 is for 450mm cylinder. Needs explicit constraints.
findings.pdf_says: GDMI FLEX text: 'Längd 850/900 för 450 mm cylinder' and 'Längd 1100/1150 för 600 mm cylinder + polisfilter'.
findings.graph_says: Length variants captured; option not machine constrained.
findings.recommendation: Add explicit conditional rules tying housing length variant, max cylinder length, and polisfilter presence.

findings.description: Graph code format fixes hinge side to 'R' in the pattern and treats left-hinge as option code 'L'. PDF example uses '...-50-R-PG-FZ' and notes 'Vänsterhängd lucka=L(left)'. This matches, but the graph pattern omits that the side token is variable (R/L).
findings.pdf_says: GDP example: GDP-600x600-50-R-PG-FZ; option: L(left).
findings.recommendation: Change format token from fixed 'R' to '{side}' with allowed values [R,L], default R.

findings.description: Same fixed-side issue: graph code formats include '-R-' rather than '-{side}-'. PDF for these families also states left-hinge option L.
findings.pdf_says: GDB/GDC/GDMI pages: option 'Vänsterhängd lucka = L (left)' and examples show '...-R-...'.
findings.recommendation: Replace 'R' with '{side}' in all relevant families; default side=R.

openai.summary: There are also two catalog inconsistencies that the graph currently handles in an ad-hoc way: (1) GDMI narrative lengths vs table lengths, and (2) a GDC FLEX row with swapped size label vs width/height columns. These need explicit, structured ‘catalog_value vs resolved_value’ handling so downstream systems can reliably select based on physical dimensions while still reproducing the printed catalog. Finally, code-format patterns should be updated to treat door side (R/L) as a variable token and to normalize accessory codes that include spaces (EXL, Filter profil) to avoid parsing failures.

findings.description: GDMI page 11 text states 'GDMI tillverkas vanligen i ZM. Ei i Rostfritt.' and material icons show only AZ and ZM. However, the graph also correctly excludes RF/SF. The graph notes a SOURCE CONFLICT about default material (text says ZM, example code says AZ). The graph chose ZM as default which is reasonable, but the example code on page 11 explicitly uses AZ as the material code (GDMI-600x600-600-R-PG-AZ), suggesting AZ may be the intended default for ordering.
findings.pdf_says: Text: 'vanligen i ZM', Example code: GDMI-600x600-600-R-PG-AZ. Material icons: AZ, ZM only.
findings.graph_says: Default material: ZM. Available: AZ, ZM. SOURCE CONFLICT noted.
findings.recommendation: This is correctly flagged as a source conflict. Consider keeping both documented but verify with manufacturer which is the true default.

findings.description: PDF page 18 shows material icons FZ, AZ, ZM for GDMI FLEX. The graph lists available materials as 'FZ, AZ, ZM (default)' which matches the icons. However, the graph states default material is ZM but the example code on page 18 uses FZ: 'GDMI-FLEX-600x600-850-R-PG-FZ'. The PDF text says 'GDMI FLEX tillverkas vanligen i ZM' but the example contradicts this.
findings.pdf_says: Material icons: FZ, AZ, ZM. Text: 'vanligen i ZM'. Example code: GDMI-FLEX-600x600-850-R-PG-FZ
findings.recommendation: Verify default material with manufacturer. The example code suggests FZ may be the standard ordering material despite text saying ZM is common.

The graph lists PT materials as 'FZ (default), AZ (on request), SF (on request), ZM (on request)' which correctly excludes RF. However, the graph does not note that SF is available (it is shown as an active icon on page 22).

findings.pdf_says: Icons: AZ, RF, FZ, ZM. Text: 'vanligen i aluzink'. Example: EXL-600 AZ

findings.description: PDF page 11 text says 'Finns som standard i två längder, 550/600 mm för korta påsfilter och 800/850 mm för långa påsfilter'. But the dimension table on page 12 shows 600/650 and 850/900. The sortiment page 3 also shows 600/650mm and 850/900mm. The graph uses 600/650 and 850/900 (table values) and documents the conflict. However, the text on page 11 says '550/600' and '800/850' which differs from the table.
findings.recommendation: Graph correctly uses table values and documents the conflict. The table and sortiment page are likely authoritative over the text description which appears to contain a typo.

findings.description: PDF page 9 shows GDB 1800x900 with weight 550/600 = 36 kg. This is anomalously low (1800x600=47kg, 1800x1200=70kg). The graph stores 36 kg and flags it as SUSPECTED_PDF_ERROR. The graph notes expected ~62kg by interpolation.

findings.description: PDF page 18 dimension table has BOTH weight columns labeled 'Vikt kg 1100/1150'. The graph notes this as SOURCE CONFLICT and interprets the first column as 850/900 weights. Looking at the values: first column (26,43,52,60,73,69,82,92) and second column (33,54,66,75,91,88,102,115), the first column values are consistently lower and match the pattern of shorter housing weights across other families.

findings.graph_says: First column interpreted as 850/900 weights. SOURCE CONFLICT documented.
findings.recommendation: Graph correctly identifies and documents this PDF labeling error. The interpretation is reasonable.

This means the label format for GDC FLEX may be HxW rather than WxH, or the Bredd/Höjd columns are swapped for this row. The graph stores this with a flag noting the inconsistency.

anthropic_opus.summary:
The Knowledge Graph demonstrates a high degree of fidelity to the PDF catalog. All 12 product families from the table of contents are present, and the dimensional data across all families has been verified row-by-row against the PDF tables. Every size entry for GDP (35 sizes), GDB (27 sizes), GDMI (35 sizes), GDC (12 sizes), GDC FLEX (6 sizes), GDMI FLEX (8 sizes), BFF (5 sizes), PFF (25 sizes), PT (5 sizes), TT (35 sizes), EXL (8 sizes), and Filter Profil (36 combinations) has been checked. All airflow values, weights, cartridge counts, filter module distributions, and dimensional measurements match the PDF source data.

The graph appropriately identifies and documents several genuine ambiguities in the PDF itself: the GDMI length discrepancy between text (550/600, 800/850) and table (600/650, 850/900), the GDB 1800x900 weight anomaly (36 kg appears to be a PDF typo), the GDMI FLEX double-labeled weight columns, and the GDC FLEX size label vs. column value inconsistency. These are flagged with SOURCE CONFLICT annotations, which is excellent practice for data integrity.

The material availability mappings are correct for all families, with proper exclusions (GDMI and GDMI FLEX correctly exclude RF/SF; PT correctly handles the greyed-out RF icon). Corrosion classes for all five materials match the PDF page 4 specifications. The code format patterns match the example codes provided in the PDF for each product family. The overall score of 72 reflects that while the core data is highly accurate, the graph could benefit from resolving the documented source conflicts with manufacturer confirmation, and the Layer 2 enrichment (environments, applications, stressors) goes beyond the PDF scope and cannot be fully validated against this catalog alone.

anthropic_opus.final_assessment: After peer review, the knowledge graph is assessed as substantially accurate with a consensus score of 82/100. The graph correctly captures all 12 product families, their dimensional data, weight tables, flow rates, and most material specifications. The most significant confirmed issues are: (1) the GDB 1800x900 weight anomaly (36 kg, likely a PDF typo) which all evaluators agree on; (2) the GDMI text vs table length conflict (550/600 vs 600/650) correctly resolved by prioritizing table data; (3) the GDMI FLEX dual-labeled weight columns correctly interpreted; (4) the GDC FLEX dimension label inconsistency faithfully reproduced. ChatGPT's critical finding about GDMI material availability is challenged and rejected—the PDF clearly shows only AZ and ZM icons with explicit text excluding stainless steel. The graph's handling of source conflicts through documentation flags is appropriate. Key areas for improvement include: modeling cabinet vs door construction separately, adding explicit max filter depth constraints, standardizing code format delimiters across product families, and clarifying the RF material availability for PT/TT transition pieces. The gemini_pro score of 98 is overly generous given the code format and construction modeling gaps, while ChatGPT's score of 72 is somewhat harsh given that its most critical finding (GDMI materials) is factually incorrect.

5. PARAMETERIZE CODE FORMAT SIDE TOKEN: Replace hardcoded 'R' with '{side}' variable (default R, option L) in code format patterns for GDP, GDB, GDC, GDMI families.
6. NORMALIZE ACCESSORY CODE FORMATS: For EXL and Filter Profil, store both the exact PDF format (with space) and a normalized hyphenated variant for parsing consistency.
7. SEPARATE CORROSION CLASS PROPERTIES: For GDP (and potentially GDB/GDC), model product_execution_corrosion_class separately from material_inherent_corrosion_class.
8. DOCUMENT GDMI/GDMI FLEX DEFAULT MATERIAL CONFLICTS: Maintain source conflict annotations where text says ZM but example codes use AZ or FZ. Flag for manufacturer verification.
9. VERIFY GDB 1800x900 SHORT WEIGHT: The 36 kg value appears anomalous. Maintain SUSPECTED_PDF_ERROR flag and consider adding a corrected estimate field.
final_report.summary:
The knowledge graph demonstrates excellent fidelity to the MANN+HUMMEL HVAC Filterskåp PDF catalog (Version 01-09-2025). All 12 product families are present with complete dimensional coverage: 232 individual size entries across GDP (35), GDB (27), GDMI (35), GDC (12), GDC FLEX (6), GDMI FLEX (8), BFF (5), PFF (25), PT (5), TT (35), EXL (8), and Filter Profil (36) have been verified against the PDF tables. All airflow values, weights, cartridge counts, filter module distributions, material corrosion classes, and code format patterns match the source data with only minor exceptions.

The graph has correctly navigated several genuine ambiguities and errors within the PDF itself: the GDMI narrative-vs-table length discrepancy (550/600 vs 600/650), the GDMI FLEX duplicate weight column headers, the GDC FLEX dimension label swap, and the GDB 1800x900 weight anomaly. These are appropriately flagged with SOURCE CONFLICT annotations. Material availability is correctly modeled, including the GDMI and GDMI FLEX restrictions (AZ/ZM only, no stainless) which were initially misread by one evaluator but confirmed correct by all three after cross-review.

The primary areas for improvement are structural rather than data accuracy issues: adding explicit max filter depth constraints for GDP, modeling polisfilter rail options as machine-actionable conditional rules rather than free text, parameterizing the door hinge side in code format patterns, normalizing accessory code formats, and resolving the minor PT/TT material availability inconsistency. The overall consensus score of 89/100 reflects a highly accurate graph with well-documented source conflicts, where remaining work is focused on schema enrichment and constraint modeling rather than data correction.
